[{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Hyperbola","page":"-","title":"Hyperbola","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"In mathematics, a hyperbola is an important conic section formed by the intersection of the double cone by a plane surface, but not necessarily at the center. A hyperbola is symmetric along the conjugate axis, and shares many similarities with the ellipse. Concepts like foci, directrix, latus rectum, eccentricity, apply to a hyperbola. A few common examples of hyperbola include the path followed by the tip of the shadow of a sundial, the scattering trajectory of subatomic particles, etc.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Here we shall aim at understanding the definition, formula of a hyperbola, derivation of the formula, and standard forms of hyperbola using the solved examples.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"A hyperbola, a type of smooth curve lying in a plane, has two pieces, called connected components or branches, that are mirror images of each other and resemble two infinite bows. A hyperbola is a set of points whose difference of distances from two foci is a constant value. This difference is taken from the distance from the farther focus and then the distance from the nearer focus. For a point mathrmP(mathrmx mathrmy) on the hyperbola and for two foci mathrmF mathrmF ', the locus of the hyperbola is P F-P F^prime=2 a.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"A hyperbola, in analytic geometry, is a conic section that is formed when a plane intersects a double right circular cone at an angle such that both halves of the cone are intersected. This intersection of the plane and cone produces two separate unbounded curves that are mirror images of each other called a hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Let us check through a few important terms relating to the different parameters of a hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Foci of hyperbola: The hyperbola has two foci and their coordinates are F(c o), and F^prime(-c 0).","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Center of Hyperbola: The midpoint of the line joining the two foci is called the center of the hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Major Axis: The length of the major axis of the hyperbola is 2a units.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Minor Axis: The length of the minor axis of the hyperbola is 2 b units.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Vertices: The points where the hyperbola intersects the axis are called the vertices. The vertices of the hyperbola are ( a, 0), (-a, 0).","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Latus Rectum of Hyperbola: The latus rectum is a line drawn perpendicular to the transverse axis of the hyperbola and is passing through the foci of the hyperbola. The length of the latus rectum of the hyperbola is 2 b^2  a. Transverse Axis: The line passing through the two foci and the center of the hyperbola is called the transverse axis of the hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Conjugate Axis: The line passing through the center of the hyperbola and perpendicular to the transverse axis is called the conjugate axis of the hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Eccentricity of Hyperbola: (e1) The eccentricity is the ratio of the distance of the focus from the center of the hyperbola, and the distance of the vertex from the center of the hyperbola. The distance of the focus is ' c ' units, and the distance of the vertex is ' a ' units, and hence the eccentricity is mathrme=mathrmc  mathrma.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Hyperbola-Equation","page":"-","title":"Hyperbola Equation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"The below equation represents the general equation of a hyperbola. Here the x-axis is the transverse axis of the hyperbola, and the y-axis is the conjugate axis of the hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"$","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"\\frac{x^{2}}{a^{2}}-\\frac{y^{2}}{b^{2}}=1 $","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Equation-of-a-Hyperbola","page":"-","title":"Equation of a Hyperbola","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Let us understand the standard form of the hyperbola equation and its derivation in detail in the following sections.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Standard-Equation-of-Hyperbola","page":"-","title":"Standard Equation of Hyperbola","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"There are two standard equations of the Hyperbola. These equations are based on the transverse axis and the conjugate axis of each of the hyperbola. The standard equation of the hyperbola is fracx^2a^2-fracy^2b^2=1 has the transverse axis as the x-axis and the conjugate axis is the y-axis. Further, another standard equation of the hyperbola is fracy^2a^2-fracx^2b^2=1 and it has the transverse axis as the y-axis and its conjugate axis is the x-axis. The below image shows the two standard forms of equations of the hyperbola.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Standard Equations of Hyperbola (Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Derivation-of-Hyperbola-Equation","page":"-","title":"Derivation of Hyperbola Equation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"As per the definition of the hyperbola, let us consider a point P on the hyperbola, and the difference of its distance from the two foci F F^prime is 2 a. P F^prime-P F=2 a Let the coordinates of P be ( x y ) and the foci be F(c 0) and F^prime(-c 0) sqrt(x+c)^2+y^2 sqrt(x-c)^2+y^2 =2 mathrma sqrt(x+c)^2+y^2 =2 mathrma+ sqrt(x-c)^2+y^2 Now we need to square on both sides to solve further. (x+c)^2+y^2=4 a^2+(x-c)^2+y^2+4 a sqrt(x-c)^2+y^2 x^2+c^2+2 c x+y^2=4 a^2+x^2+c^2-2 c x+y^2+4 a sqrt(x-c)^2+y^2 4 c x-4 a^2=4 a sqrt(x-c)^2+y^2 c x-a^2=a sqrt(x-c)^2+y^2","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Squaring on both sides and simplifying, we have. fracx^2a^2-fracy^2c^2-a^2=1 Also, we have c^2=a^2+b^2, we can substitute this in the above equation. fracx^2a^2-fracy^2b^2=1 Therefore, the standard equation of the Hyperbola is derived.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Hyperbola is an open curve that has two branches that look like mirror images of each other. For any point on any of the branches, the absolute difference between the point from foci is constant and equals to 2a, where a is the distance of the branch from the center. The Hyperbola formula helps us to find various parameters and related parts of the hyperbola such as the equation of hyperbola, the major and minor axis, eccentricity, asymptotes, vertex, foci, and semi-latus rectum.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Equation of hyperbola formula: (xx_0 )^2  a^2-(y- y_0 )^2  b^2=1 Major and minor axis formula: mathrmy=mathrmy is the major axis, and its length is 2 a, whereas x=x 0 is the minor axis, and its length is 2 b","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Eccentricity (e) of hyperbola formula: e = sqrt1+fracb^2a^2","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Asymptotes of hyperbola formula: y=y  _0^-(mathrmb  mathrma) mathrmx+(mathrmb  mathrma) mathrmx y=y  _0^+(mathrmb  mathrma) mathrmx-(mathrmb  mathrma) mathrmx Vertex of hyperbola formula: (a, y f and ( -a y ) Focus(foci) of hyperbola: (x + sqrta^2+b^2 b^y ), and (x sqrta^2+b^2 b^y )","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Semi-latus-rectum(p)-of-hyperbola-formula:","page":"-","title":"Semi-latus rectum(p) of hyperbola formula:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"p=b^2  a","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"where,","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"X","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"0 6^mathrmy are the center points.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"a = semi-major axis.\nb=\nsemi-minor axis.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Example: The equation of the hyperbola is given as ( x 5)  ^2  4^2-(y-2)^2  2^2=1. Use the hyperbola formulas to find the length of the Major Axis and Minor Axis.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Solution:","page":"-","title":"Solution:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Using the hyperbola formula for the length of the major and minor axis","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Length of major axis =2 mathrma, and length of minor axis =2 mathrmb Length of major axis =2 times 4=8, and Length of minor axis = 2 times 2=4","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Answer: The length of the major axis is 8 units, and the length of the minor axis is 4 units.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"All hyperbolas share common features, consisting of two curves, each with a vertex and a focus. The transverse axis of a hyperbola is the axis that crosses through both vertices and foci, and the conjugate axis of the hyperbola is perpendicular to it. We can observe the graphs of standard forms of hyperbola equation in the figure below. If the equation of the given hyperbola is not in standard form, then we need to complete the square to get it into standard form.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"We can observe the different parts of a hyperbola in the hyperbola graphs for standard equations given below.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Graph of Hyperbola (Image: ) (Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Here,","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"If the foci lie on the x-axis, the standard form of a hyperbola can be given as,","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"$","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"\\frac{(x-h)^{2}}{a^{2}}-\\frac{(y-k)^{2}}{b^{2}}=1 $","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"If the foci lie on the y-axis, the standard form of the hyperbola is given as,","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"$","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"\\frac{(y-k)^{2}}{a^{2}}-\\frac{(x-h)^{2}}{b^{2}}=1 $","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Coordinates of the center: (mathrmh mathrmk).\nCoordinates of vertices: ( h+a k ) and ( h-a k )\nCo-vertices correspond to b, the \" minor semi-axis length\", and coordinates of co-vertices: (h,k+b) and (h,k-b).\nFoci have coordinates ( h+c k ) and ( h-c k ). The value of c is given as, c^2=a^2+b^2.\nSlopes of asymptotes: y= pm(b  a) x.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Properties-of-a-Hyperbola","page":"-","title":"Properties of a Hyperbola","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"The following important properties related to different concepts help in understanding hyperbola better.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Asymptotes: The pair of straight lines drawn parallel to the hyperbola and assumed to touch the hyperbola at infinity. The equations of the asymptotes of the hyperbola are mathrmy= bx/a, and y = -bx/a respectively. (Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Rectangular Hyperbola: The hyperbola having the transverse axis and the conjugate axis of the same length is called the rectangular hyperbola. Here, we have 2 a=2 b, or a =mathrmb. Hence the equation of the rectangular hyperbola is equal to x^2-y^2=a^2","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Parametric Coordinates: The points on the hyperbola can be represented with the parametric coordinates ( x y ) = (asec theta, btan theta ). These parametric coordinates representing the points on the hyperbola satisfy the equation of the hyperbola. Auxilary Circle: A circle drawn with the endpoints of the transverse axis of the hyperbola as its diameter is called the auxiliary circle. The equation of the auxiliary circle of the hyperbola is x^2+y^2=a^2.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Direction Circle: The locus of the point of intersection of perpendicular tangents to the hyperbola is called the director circle. The equation of the director circle of the hyperbola is x^2+y^2=a^2-b^2.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/#Related-Articles-on-Hyperbola:","page":"-","title":"Related Articles on Hyperbola:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"The following topics are helpful for a better understanding of the hyperbola and its related concepts.","category":"page"},{"location":"Geometry/Hyperbola/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Coordinate Geometry.\nConics in Real Life\nCartesian Coordinates\nParabola","category":"page"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"This package is a collection of functions and notebooks I built as I worked through the book Foundations of Mathematics: A Preparatory Course.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"In essence, this book is a primer on basic mathematical concepts serving as a bridge into college mathematics. It starts with the very basics of arithmetical computation, moving onto basic mathematical functions, geometry and trigonometry. From there it covers more advanced topics such as basic linear algebra, calculus, probability and statistics, and concluding with complex numbers.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"The English edition is a mostly AI translation of the fourth edition of the original German text. There are a lot of dad jokes and bad puns in the text, but it is definitely clearly written and explains the concepts well. The very approachable style makes it quite suitable for self-study. I used it as a review in preparation of my study for more advanced mathematical topics.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"The code in this package is not meant to be a complete implementation of the book, but rather stuff that I created in order to gain practice and a deeper understanding of the concepts in the book. The code is all in Julia, a language I find extremely suitable for mathematical study and actually fun to code with. I make use of multiple Julia packages, not because they are necessary to implement a specific concept, but rather, in order to have an opportunity to play with and learn about some of their capabilities.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Basic-Mathematical-Functions","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Basic Mathematical Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"This section provides the documentation for all the functions I wrote to help me work through the book.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.accrued-Tuple{Real, Real, Int64}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.accrued","text":"function accrued(i::Real,p::Real,c::Int64) -> Float64\n\ni is interest, p is period (1 = one year), c is capital return accrued value\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.accrued_apr-Tuple{Real, Real, Int64}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.accrued_apr","text":"function accrued_apr(i::Real,p::Real,c::Int64) -> Float64\n\ni is interest, p is period (1 = one year), c is capital return accrued value using daily apr for interest\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.expa2x-Tuple{Real, Real}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.expa2x","text":"expa2x(a::Real,x::Real)\n\nexponential function where a > 0 and x is any Real\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.nth_root-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.nth_root","text":"nth_root(x,n) → c\n\nCalculate nth root of x handling negative x properly\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_hyperbola","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_hyperbola","text":"p\nplot_hyperbola(a::Float64=1.0, h::Float64=0.0, k::Float64=0.0)\n\nPlot hyperbola with equation y = a/(x-h) + b, where a,h and k are scaling parameters\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_hyperbola_axes_direct-Tuple{Float64, Float64}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_hyperbola_axes_direct","text":"plot_hyperbola_axes_direct(a::Float64, b::Float64)\n\nPlot hyperbola of the form (x²/a²) - (y²/b²) = 1 a and b are the semi-major and semi-minor axes\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_hyperbola_axes_varx-Tuple{Float64, Float64}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_hyperbola_axes_varx","text":"plot_hyperbola_axes_varx(a::Float64, b::Float64)\n\nPlot hyperbola of the form (x²/a²) - (y²/b²) = 1 a and b are the semi-major and semi-minor axes\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_parabola-Tuple{Any, Union{Vector{ComplexF64}, Vector{Float64}}, Float64, Float64, Float64, String}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_parabola","text":"plot_parabola(p::Polynomial, r3::Union{Vector{Float64},Vector{ComplexF64}}, a₂::Float64, a₁::Float64, a₀::Float64, str::String)\n\nPlot the parabola using the given polynomial and its roots\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_parabola_roots_amrvw","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_parabola_roots_amrvw","text":"plot_parabola_roots_amrvw(a₂::Float64, a₁::Float64=0.0, a₀::Float64=0.0) -> [ComplexF64, ComplexF64]\n\nAMRVW version of plotting parabola with roots\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_parabola_roots_polynomial","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_parabola_roots_polynomial","text":"plot_parabola_roots_polynomial(a₂::Float64, a₁::Float64=0.0, a₀::Float64=0.0) -> [ComplexF64, ComplexF64]\n\nPolynomial version of plotting parabola with roots\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.plot_parabola_roots_quadratic","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.plot_parabola_roots_quadratic","text":"plot_parabola_roots_quadratic(a₂::Float64, a₁::Float64=0.0, a₀::Float64=0.0) -> [ComplexF64, ComplexF64]\n\nQuadratic formula version of plotting parabola with roots\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#Math_Foundations.triangle_area_perim-Tuple{Float64, Float64, Float64}","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations.triangle_area_perim","text":"triangle_area_perim(a::Float64, b::Float64, c::Float64) -> Float64\n\nCalculate  ρ, area and perimeter of a triangle using Heron's formula\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#External-Documentation","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"External Documentation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"This section provides links to external documentation that replicates topics covered in the book and often provide more details. It is not an exhaustive list, but it does cover many of the important topics. Most of the links are to the LibreTexts project, which is a free online library of mathematics textbooks and resources. The links are grouped by topic.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Basic-Computation","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Basic Computation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Functions","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Geometry","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Geometry","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"Parabola\nHyperbola\nTriangle","category":"page"},{"location":"#Trigonometry","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Trigonometry","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Math_Foundations","title":"Math_Foundations","text":"Trigonometric Functions","category":"page"}]
